  "prompt": "Why do North Indians like English more than Hindi?",
  "response": "It's not accurate to say that all North Indians prefer English over Hindi. Many North Indians are proud of Hindi and use it as their primary language. However, there are some reasons why English is widely used and appreciated in North India:\n\n1. Education and opportunities\n- English is seen as a language of higher education\n- Better job prospects in professional fields\n- Used in corporate and government sectors\n\n2. Historical context\n- British colonial legacy\n- English as a link language across diverse regions\n- Perceived as a language of modernization\n\n3. Social status\n- English proficiency often associated with higher social status\n- Seen as a marker of sophistication and education\n\n4. Media and globalization\n- More exposure to English-language media\n- Global communication and internet content\n\n5. Diversity of languages in North India\n- Many regional languages coexist\n- English serves as a neutral communication medium\n\nThese factors contribute to English's popularity, but many North Indians still strongly value and speak Hindi in daily life. The preference varies among individuals and depends on personal and professional contexts.",
